## Reflection Questions

Before moving to the next chapter — which will address the practical reality of forgiving a father who is absent, dangerous, or dead — sit with these:

- What does the definition of forgiveness offered in this chapter — the withdrawal of the past's power over the present — actually mean for your specific situation? What would change in your daily life if that power were genuinely withdrawn?
- Is there a part of you that can distinguish between forgiving your father and approving of what he did? Can both be true at the same time — that he was wrong, and that you are choosing not to let his wrongness govern you any further?
- What would you do with the energy currently spent maintaining the prosecution? What in your life has been waiting for that energy to become available?
- Is there a small, first version of this choice available to you today — not the whole of it, but a beginning? What would that look like?

Forgiveness is not the end of the story. It is the moment when your story finally becomes yours to write.

That moment is available to you now.

